# Fluff Date: 2026-03-15 18:47:47
<overview>
<p>The Grenadier II is a heavy-class battlesuit produced by General Motors as an evolution of the original Grenadier design. Incorporating Clan-specification armor technology on an Inner Sphere chassis, the suit achieves comparable protection to its predecessor at a reduced weight of fifteen hundred kilograms. This lighter mass enables OmniMech transport, a capability the heavier Grenadier lacks. The suit features dual modular weapon mounts accommodating a wide variety of loadout configurations and a basic manipulator for environmental interaction. Mixed Inner Sphere and Clan technology gives the Grenadier II a competitive edge in firepower and protection, though the hybrid construction carries a maintenance burden that field technicians have found challenging to manage.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>Configuration B replaces the left arm weapon with a battle armor C3 computer system, transforming the Grenadier II into a networked coordination platform. The body-mounted Clan-specification long-range missile launcher with eight reloads provides indirect fire capability at extended range. The C3 link shares targeting data across networked formations, improving accuracy for all connected units. This configuration trades direct-fire lethality for force multiplication, making it most effective within a larger C3 network alongside more heavily armed suits or vehicles. The long-range missiles allow troopers to contribute firepower from covered positions, reducing exposure. Without the network link active, the configuration offers only modest standalone combat capability, relying entirely on the missile launcher for offensive output.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>Augmented five-trooper Configuration B squads maximize the C3 network's coverage by adding another data node to the formation. The Federated Suns Armored Cavalry fielded five-suit teams in its forward reconnaissance elements, where the additional trooper provided security while the squad focused on network coordination and target designation. The long-range missile loadout allowed these squads to contribute meaningful firepower without abandoning their observation positions.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>General Motors developed the Grenadier II at their Talcott facility as a lighter evolution of the original Grenadier already fielded by the AFFS. The suit entered service in 3137, taking advantage of Clan-specification components made available through Republic of the Sphere trade channels. The AFFS had long proven resistant to fielding heavy battle armor, preferring either the raw power of assault-weight suits or the greater mobility of medium designs. The Grenadier II's reduced mass and mixed-technology construction addressed both concerns, earning acceptance where the heavier original had faced reluctance.</p><p>The Republic Armed Forces also acquired the design through Republic-friendly agencies in the Federated Suns. The First Davion Guards were among the earliest units to field the Mk. II, pairing them with Ziblers from the Eighteenth Shibata Recon Regiment as quick reaction forces against Senate rebels. The RAF reserved one configuration exclusively for Republic use, equipping it with indirect fire systems for self-supporting artillery capability. The Republic later exploited this configuration for covert raids beyond the Fortress walls, using what appeared to be Davion equipment to divert suspicion from Republic involvement in border operations.</p>
</history>

